"meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Hans, Heinz, Elke, Florian, Franz, Gerda, Konrad, Lotti, Reinhard.","German:","nickname for a person with red hair, from an inflected form of   Roth   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Rotering","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Mathias.","German: patronymic from   Rother   2."]},{"name":"Roth","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): nickname for a person with red hair, from Middle High German <i>rōt</i>, German <i>rot</i> ‘red’. As a Jewish name it is at least in part artificial: its frequency as a Jewish surname is disproportionate to the number of Jews who, one may reasonably assume, were red-headed during the period of surname adoption. This form of the German surname (especially in this sense and in the sense 2 below) is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), where it is most common, and in some other European countries, e.g. Czechia and Croatia.","German and English (Middlesex): topographic name for someone who lived on land that had been cleared, from Old High German <i>rod</i>, Middle English <i>roth(e)</i> (Old English <i>roth</i>) ‘clearing’. In England, the name may also be a habitational name from any of the places like Rothend in Ashdon (Essex), Roe End in Markyate (Hertfordshire), Roe Green in Hatfield (Hertfordshire), or Roe Green in Sandon (Hertfordshire).","German: from a short form of any of various ancient Germanic personal names with the first element <i>hrōd</i> ‘renown’. Compare   Rode   1,   Ross   4."]},{"name":"Rotter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Gerhard, Hans, Horst, Markus, Siegried.","German: variant of   Rother  .","German: status or occupational name for the foreman or leader of a group or association of men, for example a market co-op, a community, or a work gang, from an agent derivative of Middle High German <i>rotte</i> ‘team, gang’."]}]},{"name":"Watson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish, English, and Irish: patronymic meaning ‘son of <i>Wat</i>’, a pet form of   Walter   that was particularly common in Scotland and northern England. See   Watt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Walter","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Watson of Rothes married Watson of Rothes before 1250, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1250–1320":"1250–1320","–Female":"Surnud","1320":"1320","1220":"1220","before 1250":"enne 1250","1250":"1250","Europe":"Europe","Edengarioch, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1220–Male":"1220–Kuollut","1250–1320":"1250–1320","–Female":"Kuollut","1320":"1320","1220":"1220","before 1250":"ennen vuotta 1250","1250":"1250","Europe":"Europe","Edengarioch, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","1220–Male":"1220–Décédé","1250–1320":"1250–1320","–Female":"Décédée","1320":"1320","1220":"1220","before 1250":"avant 1250","1250":"1250","Europe":"Europe","Edengarioch, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Watson of Rothes a épousé Watson of Rothes avant 1250, à Europe. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"–":"Verstorben","1220–Male":"1220–Verstorben","1250–1320":"1250–1320","–Female":"Verstorben","1320":"1320","1220":"1220","before 1250":"vor 1250","1250":"1250","Europe":"Europa","Edengarioch, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Schottland, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Watson of Rothes hat vor 1250 in Europa Watson of Rothes geheiratet. Sie hatten mind